"Stott P.A., Tett S.F.B., Jones G.S., Allen M.R., Mitchell J.F.B., Jenkins G.J.","External control of 20th century temperature by natural and anthropogenic forcings",2000,"Science","290","5499",,"2133","2137",,,10.1126/science.290.5499.2133,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0034671839&partnerID=40&md5=8b694df0d3dfccbc0d142b725d4daf8f","Met Office, Hadley Ctr. Climate Prediction/Res., Bracknell, Berkshire RG12 2SY, United Kingdom","Stott, P.A., Met Office, Hadley Ctr. Climate Prediction/Res., Bracknell, Berkshire RG12 2SY, United Kingdom; Tett, S.F.B., Met Office, Hadley Ctr. Climate Prediction/Res., Bracknell, Berkshire RG12 2SY, United Kingdom; Jones, G.S., Met Office, Hadley Ctr. Climate Prediction/Res., Bracknell, Berkshire RG12 2SY, United Kingdom; Allen, M.R., Met Office, Hadley Ctr. Climate Prediction/Res., Bracknell, Berkshire RG12 2SY, United Kingdom; Mitchell, J.F.B., Met Office, Hadley Ctr. Climate Prediction/Res., Bracknell, Berkshire RG12 2SY, United Kingdom; Jenkins, G.J., Met Office, Hadley Ctr. Climate Prediction/Res., Bracknell, Berkshire RG12 2SY, United Kingdom","A comparison of observations with simulations of a coupled ocean-atmosphere general circulation model shows that both natural and anthropogenic factors have contributed significantly to 20th century temperature changes. The model successfully simulates global mean and large-scale land temperature variations, indicating that the climate response on these scales is strongly influenced by external factors. More than 80% of observed multidecadal-scale global mean temperature variations and more than 60% of 10- to 50-year land temperature variations are due to changes in external forcings. Anthropogenic global warming under a standard emissions scenario is predicted to continue at a rate similar to that observed in recent decades.",,"air temperature; atmosphere-ocean coupling; climate forcing; general circulation model; twentieth century; air temperature; article; force; global climate; greenhouse effect; priority journal; sea; simulation; temperature dependence",,,,,,"Santer, B.D., (1996) Nature, 382, p. 39; Hegerl, G.C., (1996) J. Clim., 9, p. 2281; Tett, S.F.B., Stott, P.A., Allen, M.R., Ingram, W.J., Mitchell, J.F.B., (1999) Nature, 399, p. 569; Mann, M.E., Bradley, R.S., Hughes, M.K., (1999) Geophys. Res. Lett., 26, p. 759; Crowley, T.J., (2000) Science, 289, p. 270; Kelly, P.M., Wigley, T.M.L., (1992) Nature, 360, p. 328; Andronova, N.G., Schlesinger, M.E., (2000) Geophys. Res. Lett., 27, p. 2137; Mitchell, J.F.B., Johns, T.C., Gregory, J.M., Tett, S.F.B., (1995) Nature, 376, p. 501; Hegerl, G.C., (1997) Clim. Dyn., 13, p. 613; Tett, S.F.B., (2000) Hadley Centre Technical Note No. 19, , Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction and Research, Bracknell, UK; Crowley, T.J., Kim, K.-Y., (1999) Geophys. Res. Lett., 26, p. 1901; Lean, J., Rind, D., (1998) J. Clim., 11, p. 3069; Stott, P.A., (2001) Clim. Dyn., 17, p. 1; Delworth, T.L., Knutson, T.R., (2000) Science, 287, p. 2246; Schimel, D., (1996) Climate Change 1995: The Science of Climate Change, pp. 65-131. , J. T. Houghton et al., Eds. (Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge), chap. 4; Gordon, C., (2001) Clim. Dyn., 16, p. 147; Pope, V.D., Gallani, M.L., Rowntree, P.R., Stratton, R.A., (2000) Clim. Dyn., 16, p. 123; notenoteTwomey, S.A., (1974) Atmos. Environ., 8 (1251); Sato, M., Hanson, J.E., McCormick, M.P., Pollack, J.B., (1993) J. Geophys. Res., 98, p. 22987; Lean, J., Beer, J., Bradley, R., (1995) Geophys. Res. Lett., 22, p. 3195; Nakicenovic, N., (2000) IPCC Special Report on Emissions Scenarios, , Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge; notenotenotenotenoteCane, M.A., (1997) Science, 275, p. 957; notenoteBoer, G.J., (2000) Clim. Dyn., 16, p. 469; Collins, M., Allen, M.R., (2000) Hadley Centre Technical Note No. 21, , Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction and Research, Bracknell, UK; noteAllen, M.R., Tett, S.F.B., (1999) Clim. Dyn., 15, p. 419; Stott, P.A., Tett, S.F.B., Jones, G.S., Allen, M.